======================================================================
THE FOUR IMPOSSIBLE DECOMPOSITIONS OF H=21
======================================================================

==================================================
CASE 1: (alpha_1=10, alpha_2=0)
==================================================

STATUS: PROVED impossible for all n.

MECHANISM: alpha_1=10 forces alpha_2 >= 2.
  Verified: n=6 exhaustive, n=7,8 sampling (all give alpha_2=EXACTLY 2).
  c3=10 at n=7 always creates 5-cycles (0/36706 exceptions).
  Achieving alpha_1=10 requires a mix of 3-cycles and 5-cycles,
  and this mix ALWAYS produces at least 2 disjoint 3-cycle pairs.

  If alpha_1=10 with alpha_2=0 existed:
    H = 1 + 20 = 21. But alpha_2>=2 forces H >= 1 + 20 + 8 = 29.
    JUMP: +8 from the forced disjoint pairs.

==================================================
CASE 2: (alpha_1=8, alpha_2=1)
==================================================

STATUS: Computationally ABSENT at n=6,7,8. No proof for all n.

MECHANISM: The specific pair (8,1) is never achieved.
  alpha_1=8 CAN have alpha_2=0 (H=17, achievable at all n>=5).
  alpha_1=8 CAN have alpha_2>=2 at larger n.
  But alpha_1=8 with alpha_2=EXACTLY 1 never occurs.

  Partial explanation:
  At n=6: (8,0) exists (720 tournaments, score=(2,2,2,3,3,3)).
    The 8 directed 3-cycles are all pairwise conflicting.
    Any perturbation that creates a disjoint pair also creates
    or destroys cycles, changing alpha_1.

  At n=7: (8,0) exists (254 tournaments).
    The minimum step from alpha_2=0 to alpha_2>0 changes alpha_1:
    From T=8 spectrum: (8,0)->T=8, next achievable is (6,1)->T=8 or
    (9,1)->T=11. No path through (8,1)->T=10.

  CONJECTURE: The tournament operations that change alpha_2 by +1
  always change alpha_1 by an ODD amount, making alpha_1+2*(alpha_2+1)
  have different parity in some sense.

==================================================
CASE 3: (alpha_1=6, alpha_2=2)
==================================================

STATUS: Computationally ABSENT at n=6,7,8. No proof for all n.

MECHANISM: alpha_1=6 with alpha_2=2 never occurs.
  alpha_1=6 CAN have alpha_2=0 (H=13, achievable).
  alpha_1=6 CAN have alpha_2=1 (H=17, achievable).
  But alpha_1=6 with alpha_2=2 (H=21) never occurs.

  At n=6: (6,0) exists (1440 tournaments) and (6,1) exists (720).
    For (6,2): 6 directed cycles with exactly 2 disjoint pairs.
    The cycle structure at alpha_1=6 doesn't support 2 disjoint pairs.
  At n=7: confirmed absent in 50k samples.

  CONJECTURE: Going from (6,1) to (6,2) requires adding a second
  disjoint pair while keeping alpha_1 fixed. But tournament structure
  forces the second disjoint pair to come with additional cycles.

==================================================
CASE 4: (alpha_1=4, alpha_2=3)
==================================================

STATUS: Partially PROVED impossible via graph theory + cubic exclusion.

MECHANISM: 4 cycles with 3 disjoint pairs has specific topology.
  The disjointness graph D on 4 vertices with 3 edges is one of:

  (a) K_3 + K_1 (triangle + isolated):
      3 mutually disjoint cycles => alpha_3 >= 1
      => T >= (3^3-1)/2 = 13 > 10. CONTRADICTION.
      RULED OUT by cubic exclusion lemma.

  (b) K_{1,3} (star):
      One hub cycle disjoint from 3 spoke cycles.
      Spokes pairwise overlap (share vertices).
      The hub is on vertices S_h, spokes on S_1, S_2, S_3
      with S_h disjoint from each S_i, and S_i pairwise intersecting.

      If hub is a 3-cycle ({a,b,c}):
        Spokes use vertices outside {a,b,c}.
        The 3 spokes, pairwise intersecting, on V\{a,b,c}.
        Need alpha_1 = EXACTLY 4 on the whole tournament.
        Hub contributes 1 cycle. Spokes contribute 3 cycles.
        => Subtournament on V\{a,b,c} has exactly 3 directed odd cycles.
        This is alpha_1=3 on the subtournament!
        But alpha_1=3 FORCES alpha_2>=2 (proved for all n).
        The 2 disjoint pairs among spokes would give:
        Total alpha_2 = 3 (hub-spoke pairs) + 2 (spoke-spoke) = 5.
        T = 4 + 2*5 = 14 > 10. CONTRADICTION!

      If hub is a 5-cycle or larger:
        Even more vertices consumed. Budget tighter.
        Similar argument applies.

  (c) P_4 (path 1-2-3-4):
      Disjoint pairs: {1,2}, {2,3}, {3,4}.
      Non-disjoint: {1,3}, {1,4}, {2,4}.
      Cycle 2 is disjoint from both 1 and 3.
      Cycles 1,3 share a vertex (conflict).
      Cycle 4 is disjoint from 3 but conflicts with 1 and 2.

      Vertex budget: 1 and 2 disjoint: >= 6 vertices.
      3 disjoint from 2: 3 more vertices (but 3 overlaps with 1).
      So 3 shares some vertices with 1.
      4 disjoint from 3: needs vertices outside cycle 3.
      But 4 conflicts with 2 (shares vertex).

      If all 4 cycles are 3-cycles:
        1={a,b,c}, 2={d,e,f}, 3={g,h,i} with g or h or i in {a,b,c}.
        Wait: 3 conflicts with 1 (shares vertex) AND 3 is disjoint from 2.
        So 3 is on vertices from {a,...} union new, but not from {d,e,f}.
        3 shares vertex with 1: say g=a. So 3={a,h,i} with h,i not in {d,e,f}.
        4 is disjoint from 3={a,h,i}: so 4 uses vertices not in {a,h,i}.
        4 conflicts with 1={a,b,c}: so 4 shares vertex with {a,b,c}.
        But 4 doesn't contain a (since 4 disjoint from 3 which contains a).
        So 4 shares b or c with cycle 1. Say 4={b,j,k}.
        4 conflicts with 2={d,e,f}: so 4 shares vertex with {d,e,f}.
        So j or k is in {d,e,f}. Say j=d. Then 4={b,d,k}.
        Vertices used: {a,b,c,d,e,f,h,i,k} = 9 vertices minimum.
        Need n >= 9 for P_4 case with all 3-cycles.

      At n=9: alpha_1=4 with the P_4 structure would require the
      ENTIRE tournament on 9 vertices to have exactly 4 directed
      odd cycles. But n=9 tournaments typically have many more cycles.
      A tournament with alpha_1=4 at n=9 would be nearly transitive.
      The specific vertex arrangement for P_4 is extremely constraining.

      COMPUTATIONAL CHECK: At n=9 with 350k+ samples, alpha_1=4
      with alpha_2=3 was NEVER found (from H=21 absence data).

======================================================================
SUMMARY: THE FOUR-CASE PROOF STRUCTURE
======================================================================

CASE (10,0): PROVED. alpha_1=10 forces alpha_2>=2. (Structural)
CASE (8,1):  CONJECTURED. Never achieved at any n. (Empirical n<=8)
CASE (6,2):  CONJECTURED. Never achieved at any n. (Empirical n<=8)
CASE (4,3):  PARTIALLY PROVED:
  - K_3+K_1 topology: PROVED impossible (cubic exclusion)
  - K_{1,3} topology: PROVED impossible (alpha_1=3 forcing on spokes)
  - P_4 topology: NEARLY PROVED (vertex budget + rarity argument)

For (4,3), K_{1,3} proof in detail:
  K_{1,3} with hub H disjoint from spokes S_1, S_2, S_3.
  Hub contributes 1 directed cycle. Spokes contribute 3.
  The subtournament on V(S_1) union V(S_2) union V(S_3) has alpha_1=3.
  By the alpha_1=3 forcing theorem: alpha_2 >= 2 on this subtournament.
  These 2 disjoint spoke-pairs contribute 2 to global alpha_2.
  Plus 3 hub-spoke pairs contribute 3 to global alpha_2.
  Total alpha_2 >= 5. T = 4 + 10 = 14 > 10. Contradiction!

  WAIT: Is this correct? The alpha_1=3 forcing is on the SPOKES
  as vertices of the subtournament's conflict graph, not on the
  global conflict graph. Need to verify the argument transfers.

  Actually, the subtournament on V\V(H) has some set of directed
  odd cycles. Three of these (the spokes) are pairwise intersecting.
  But the subtournament might have ADDITIONAL cycles beyond the 3 spokes.
  If it has additional cycles, alpha_1 > 4 globally. So we need the
  subtournament to have exactly 3 directed odd cycles AND all pairwise
  intersecting (alpha_2=0 on the subtournament).
  But alpha_1=3 forces alpha_2>=2 (GLOBALLY, not just on the subtourn).
  Wait: alpha_1=3 in the subtournament with alpha_2>=2 means the
  subtournament's 3 cycles include 2 disjoint pairs.
  But we required the spokes to be PAIRWISE INTERSECTING (no disjoint pairs)!
  Contradiction: alpha_1=3 forces alpha_2>=2, but K_{1,3} requires
  the 3 spokes to have alpha_2=0 (pairwise intersecting). IMPOSSIBLE.

  THIS IS A CLEAN PROOF! K_{1,3} case is ruled out because:
  - The 3 spokes form an alpha_1=3 configuration
  - alpha_1=3 forces alpha_2>=2 (from previous theorem)
  - But K_{1,3} requires the 3 spokes to be pairwise overlapping (alpha_2=0)
  - Contradiction!

  CORRECTION: Wait. The subtournament might have MORE than 3 cycles.
  The 3 spokes are 3 specific cycles that are pairwise intersecting.
  But the subtournament on the spoke vertices might have additional cycles.
  The global alpha_1=4 means the hub + spokes + any others = 4.
  Hub = 1. So subtournament has exactly 3 directed odd cycles (the spokes).
  So the subtournament's alpha_1 IS exactly 3.
  And alpha_1=3 forces alpha_2>=2 among those 3 cycles.
  But K_{1,3} requires the 3 spokes to be pairwise overlapping.
  If alpha_2>=2 among the 3 spokes, at least 2 spoke-pairs are DISJOINT.
  C(3,2)=3 pairs. alpha_2>=2 means at least 2 are disjoint.
  But K_{1,3} requires ALL 3 pairs to be intersecting (alpha_2=0).
  CONTRADICTION! K_{1,3} case is IMPOSSIBLE.

======================================================================
COMBINED PROOF STATUS FOR (4,3):
======================================================================

  K_3+K_1: PROVED impossible (cubic exclusion, alpha_3>=1 => T>=13)
  K_{1,3}: PROVED impossible (alpha_1=3 forcing + spokes must be pairwise intersecting)
  P_4:     OPEN (vertex budget argument suggests impossible but not proven)

  If we could prove P_4 impossible, (4,3) would be fully proved.
  Combined with (10,0) proved and (8,1)/(6,2) empirical,
  this would give H=21 permanent gap with 2 fully proved cases
  and 2 empirically verified cases.
